hands_on_practices.problem:
Consider a simplified one-dimensional model of a component in a nanoelectronic device. An electron of mass $m$ propagates along the $x$-axis. It encounters a thin insulating layer of width $L$. This layer can be modeled as a rectangular potential barrier of constant height $V_0$. That is, the potential energy $V(x)$ is defined as:
$$
V(x) = \begin{cases}
V_0  \text{for } 0  x  L \\
0  \text{otherwise}
\end{cases}
$$
A special operating condition is tuned such that the total energy of the incident electron, $E$, is exactly equal to the barrier height, $V_0$.

Your task is to determine the transmission coefficient, $T$, for the electron under this specific condition ($E=V_0$). The transmission coefficient is defined as the ratio of the probability current of the transmitted wave to the probability current of the incident wave.

Find a closed-form analytic expression for the transmission coefficient $T$ in terms of the electron mass $m$, the barrier width $L$, the barrier height $V_0$, and the reduced Planck constant $\hbar$.
